bug.short_desc: [ataspectj] Assymetry between AfterReturning/Throwing and other advice annotation

long_desc.thetext:
Compared to other advice annotations, AfterReturning and AfterThrowing has an additional 'pointcut' property (that overrides the 'value' property). This is, IMO, unnecessary learning burden on users. This can be fixed in two ways:
1. (My preference -- one less thing to learn) Deprecate the 'pointcut' property eventually removing it. This should be big burden on users since the change required is pretty trivial. 2. Add the 'pointcut' property to all advice annotations.
Correction: This should be big burden --> This should not be big burden

Thinking more, I have even stronger preference for the first option (deprecate the "pointcut" attribute).
It is not just other kind of advice, but none of the other constructs follow this kind of arrangement. For example, @DeclareParents doesn't specify "types" attribute (that would take precedence over "value"), nor we have "association" attribute for @Aspect. I think fewer attributes with the "value" attribute specifying the dominant property (expression for pointcut, pointcut for advice, types for declare parents, and association for aspect) of the construct is a simple to explain and easy to maintain approach.

bug.short_desc: When connecting to a non-existing debugger or wrong version debugger - no message appears

long_desc.thetext:
1. Connect to a remote non-existing debug server or 2. Connect to a remote servger with debugger version < 5.2.1
The GUI just waits.we don't know what's going on. Expected - a relevant message.

Partial fix was implemented.
We divide this bug into 2 parts. One is dealing with the internal debugger, while the other is dealing with the remote debugger (web server).
1. When trying to debug using the internal debugger while the php.ini did not direct to a valid debugger, the launch was stuck (forever) in the launches view. The fix for this issue is to display an error message when the process terminated while we got no debugger response (e.g. no IDebugTarget). In this case, we present an error message and remove the launch.
2. When trying to debug using a PHP web server, the situation is a bit more complex. The fix for this situation is to keep track on the responses we get from the server. In case we do not get any response for a period of 10 seconds, we declare a problem and terminate the session.
For now, I choose not to put this bug as resolved for several reasons: 1. A progress indication should appear while waiting too long for a server response. 2. Ask the user to continue and wait for another period of time, or to terminate. 3. (maybe) add a preferences value for the time we wait until we declare a problem.
-SG

bug.short_desc: CP is disappeared in Configuration view after child activity is contributed

long_desc.thetext:
Steps To Reproduce: 1. create CP1 and a sub activity: 'activity_base' 2. create CP2, then create a sub phase and a sub activity: 'activity_contri' 3. contributes activity_contri to activity_base 4. refresh the Configuration view -->problem: CP2 disappear from the Configuration view -->expect result: only hide the activity_contri, the CP2 and the phase under it should be visible.
More information: 1. CP2 should be visible even when it has only one activity 2. not a regression, and the same problem for DP

This is not a bug. It works in this it by design. When we implement the activity contribution, its purpose is to contribute additional stuff into an existing activity, the contributor are not supposed to involve into the tree navigation. The main reason for this limitation is to avoid complicated filtering in the UI and possible deadlock in realization.
If this limitation needs to be removed, please submit a change request.
Resolve this as it's by design. It's logical not to make a contributor navigate-able.

replace should be treated in the same way as contribute. I.e. if a CP or DP has activities contributing to or replaces other activities, this CP or DP is not navigatable. This is just by design to simplify the work.
This assumes user to not adding activity variability with the same process, instead, he/she should create a seperate, non-navigatable process with the contributes and replaces. and should understand that such processes are not navigatable, i.e they will not appear in the navigation tree.
I have modified the code to enforce this. I.e. a CP with activity replacers will disapear as well.
Please fill RFE if this limitation is not acceptable. Also we should put this into the release notes.

bug.short_desc: Ability to store test definitions in any database

long_desc.thetext:
It would be great if there is a way for test definitions created from the TPTP EMF models (testprofile and behavior) be persisted in database (we can get the connection information from user)
We tried an implementation of this using teneo (http://www.eclipse.org/emft/projects/teneo/#teneo). It works great!! Needed to add annotations to TPFVerdictReason for making this work.

This sounds interesting. We are looking to use an RDB store in 4.4 to get more scalability for all our models. Hibernate apparently has some licencing problems, but there are other options to hibernate. It would be great to understand your motivation to do this and your experiences

(In reply to comment #1) > This sounds interesting. We are looking to use an RDB store in 4.4 to get more > scalability for all our models. > Hibernate apparently has some licencing problems, but there are other options > to hibernate. > It would be great to understand your motivation to do this and your experiences >
I work for Sungard Higher Education (http://www.sungardhe.com/). Our team is building a test framework that is capable of, among other things,
1) Understanding various test assets available in different formats; convert and store them in U2TP - We are using TPTP's EMF Models for storing the test definitions 2) Translating the test assets stored in U2TP to different formats (Junit, LR Scripts, RFT Scripts) - We are using EMF Persistence API's for this 3) Integrating with various testing tools - LoadRunner, Rational Function Tester etc, QTP., - We are using Oracle BPEL to define test processes and for executing them, have not checked the choreography engine of TPTP. 4) Capture test results from these tools and store them in a common format - we are planning to use TPTP's result history model for this
We are using the TPTP platform project heavily and in particular the EMF models for test definition, configuration and results. Over this we are building an UI for importing test definitions (that are in various formats right now), translating tests and for executing them. We had some difficulty understanding and using the behavior model.
We are also planning to generate business analytics from test definitions and results. For this reason we need to store the assets in db.

2) I have verified using XMLPad 3.0 that the xml file violates the unique constraint specified in the xsd file. Notice that the xpath attribute of the <selector> element can be specified both as "action" and "./action". I have tried both.

Valentin, I'm guessing if there is an issue here it'd be due to some esoteric option that needs to be set in the Xerces validator. You might want to contact Michael Glavassevich (here at IBM) to see if he knows of any magic (if a quick glance at the Xerces docs don't help).

amples you provided, fixed the schema location to resolve properly on my machine then tried validating the schema and the XML instance document. The schema validates fine and the XML instance is reported invalid, but not because of the unique constraint being violated. This is the error I am seeing:
Severity and Description Path Resource Location Creation Time Id cvc-complex-type.2.4.a: Invalid content was found starting with element 'action'. One of '{action}' is expected. Unique UniqueExample.xml line 5 1168998486106 4873
This is mainly due to the way the XSD validator, based on Xerces, deals with validating instances based on schemas with elementFormDefault="unqualified" (which is the default). While somewhat counter intuitive, you can slightly modify the XML instance to look like this, and still be correct:
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?> <foo:example xmlns:foo="http://www.example.org/UniqueExample" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.example.org/UniqueExample UniqueExample.xsd"> <action id="1" /> <action id="2" /> <action id="1" /> </foo:example>
Note the prefix I added instead of using no prefix for the top level element. Once you do that and revalidate you will then notice the unique constraint violation message in the problems view:
Severity and Description Path Resource Location Creation Time Id Duplicate unique value [1] declared for identity constraint of element "example". Unique UniqueExample.xml line 7 1168998731696 4875
Please let me know if you see the same behaviour.

1) Shouldn't we open another bug, regarding the XSD validator not working properly when using documents with default unqualified namespaces, like I did? 2) Surely this happened, and will happen, to other people as well? I checked a couple of xml/xml-schema tutorials on-line, and they all seem to use unqualified elements in their xml examples.

Regarding your concern about the XSD validator: I think the behaviour you are seeing is the behaviour exhibited by Xerces, which the XSD validator simply wraps with an Eclipse specific layer.

In the mean time I'll try contacting the Xerces folks to try to find out more.

Jonathan, here's what I found out regarding the Xerces XML/XSD validation (thanks Michael).
This is a matter of understanding how XML namespaces work and how the target namespace of a local element declaration in an XML schema is determined. By default, locally declared elements ([1] see the section starting with "An element declaration as in the first case above...") have no target namespace. In the instance document, if there's a default namespace declaration in scope [2] unprefixed element names have a namespace. By definition such elements can never match a local element declaration which has no target namespace.
[1] http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-1/#declare-element [2] http://www.w3.org/TR/2006/REC-xml-names-20060816/#defaulting
I hope this clarifies why the instance document has to be the way I suggested to be properly validated by the Xerces validator.

bug.short_desc: We need a way to get notified about ANT failures

long_desc.thetext: WTP uses ANT launches in separate VM to deploy to servers. Currently there is no way to get notified about the failures and progress on the build file. I have investigated a way to subscribe to RemoteAntBuildListener but that was not possible. It would be great if we could add an observer to a launch configuration and get notified about the progress and errors of the build (possibly through RemoteAntBuildListener)

Vanilla Apache Ant allows you to add build listeners to any build and therefore you can receive all the notifications that the RemoteAntBuildListener receives.
See http://ant.apache.org/manual/listeners.html but essentially you would specify -listener YourBuildListener as a program argument within your Ant launch configuration.

I do not have a my own launch configuration implementation, I am using platform provided ant launch configuration. Also just having a listener will not do it since the listener needs to connect to running eclipse instance and notify the event. Of course having own launch configuration and RemoteAntBuildListener is a possibility but this basically means that I need to copy/implement everything that already exists on the platform including the Console(I am not giving up the console). Same VM launches already reports build failures and I think this is an important piece of missing functionality from separate VM launches.

I need to fully understand what you are attempting to achieve and how.
I know little about WTP..you are programmatically launching an Ant build?

Yes, when a project needs to be published to server, we create a launch configuration with publish time calculated properties and targets and launch in a seperate VM. Everything works fine except we do not get notified about the build failures, which causes the publishing state of the project to be false(and this causes bad user experience). The immediate need is to get notified about the failures but any other information may allow us to inform users better about the progress.
So for the ant launch configuration you are creating and launching I do not understand why you cannot specify a program argument for an Ant build listener to listen for the build failed event?

My launches are on a separate VM, because of that my listener would be instanced and notified on that VM instance. I am not aware of any way to modify UI elements on the eclipse instance from a seperate VM. I think this is exactly the problem RemoteAntBuildListener solves by creating a server socket that eclipse's (added by -logger) ant logger can connect and fetch build info for displaying on the console.
Yes you are correct. Your build listener would need to communicate back to the other VM.
